# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rich-terminal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] ANSI sequences were introduced in the 1970s to replace vendor-specific sequences and became widespread in the computer equipment market by the early 1980s.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Although hardware text terminals have become increasingly rare in the 21st century, the relevance of the ANSI standard persists because a great majority of terminal emulators and command consoles interpret at least a portion of the ANSI standard.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Almost all manufacturers of video terminals added vendor-specific escape sequences to perform operations such as placing the cursor at arbitrary positions on the screen.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The Hazeltine 1500 had a similar feature, invoked using `~`, `DC1` and then the X and Y positions separated with a comma.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] While the two terminals had identical functionality in this regard, different control sequences had to be used to invoke them.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As these sequences were different for different terminals, elaborate libraries such as termcap ("terminal capabilities") and utilities such as tput had to be created so programs could use the same API to work with any terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In addition, many of these terminals required sending numbers (such as row and column) as the binary values of the characters; for some programming languages, and for systems that did not use ASCII internally, it was often difficult to turn a number into the correct character.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The ANSI standard attempted to address these problems by making a command set that all terminals would use and requiring all numeric information to be transmitted as ASCII numbers.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The first standard in the series was **ECMA-48**, adopted in 1976.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] It was a continuation of a series of character coding standards, the first one being ECMA-6 from 1965, a 7-bit standard from which ISO 646 originates.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The name "ANSI escape sequence" dates from 1979 when ANSI adopted ANSI X3.64.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The ANSI X3L2 committee collaborated with the ECMA committee TC 1 to produce nearly identical standards.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] These two standards were merged into an international standard, ISO 6429.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In 1994, ANSI withdrew its standard in favor of the international standard.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The first popular video terminal to support these sequences was the Digital VT100, introduced in 1978.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This model was very successful in the market, which sparked a variety of VT100 clones, among the earliest and most popular of which was the much more affordable Zenith Z-19 in 1979.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Others included the Qume QVT-108, Televideo TVI-970, Wyse WY-99GT as well as optional "VT100" or "VT103" or "ANSI" modes with varying degrees of compatibility on many other brands.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The popularity of these gradually led to more and more software (especially bulletin board systems and other online services) assuming the escape sequences worked, leading to almost all new terminals and emulator programs supporting them.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In 1981, ANSI X3.64 was adopted for use in the US government by FIPS publication 86.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Later, the US government stopped duplicating industry standards, so FIPS pub.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] ECMA-48 has been updated several times and is currently at its 5th edition, from 1991.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] It is also adopted by ISO and IEC as standard **ISO/IEC 6429**.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] A version is adopted as a Japanese Industrial Standard, as JIS X 0211.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Related standards include ITU T.61, the Teletex standard, and the **ISO/IEC 8613**, the Open Document Architecture standard (mainly ISO/IEC 8613-6 or ITU T.416).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The two systems share many escape codes with the ANSI system, with extensions that are not necessarily meaningful to computer terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Both systems quickly fell into disuse, but ECMA-48 does mark the extensions used in them as reserved.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In the early 1980s, large amounts of software directly used these sequences to update screen displays.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This included everything on VMS (which assumed DEC terminals), most software designed to be portable on CP/M home computers, and significant amounts of Unix software, as it was easier to use than the termcap libraries.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Terminal emulators for communicating with remote machines almost always implement ANSI escape codes.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This includes anything written to communicate with bulletin-board systems on home and personal computers.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] On Unix terminal emulators such as xterm also can communicate with software running on the same machine, and thus software running in X11 under a terminal emulator could assume the ability to write these sequences.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As computers got more powerful even built-in displays started supporting them, allowing software to be portable between CP/M systems.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] There were attempts to extend the escape sequences to support printers and as an early PDF-like document storage format, the Open Document Architecture.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The IBM PC, introduced in 1981, did not support these or any other escape sequences for updating the screen.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Only a few control characters (BEL, CR, LF, BS) were interpreted by the underlying BIOS.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Any display effects had to be done with BIOS calls, which were notoriously slow, or by directly manipulating the IBM PC hardware.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This made any interesting software non-portable and led to the need to duplicate details of the display hardware in PC Clones.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] DOS version 2.0 included an optional device driver named ANSI.SYS.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Poor performance, and the fact that it was not installed by default, meant software rarely (if ever) took advantage of it.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The Windows Console did not support ANSI escape sequences, nor did Microsoft provide any method to enable them.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some replacements such as JP Software's TCC (formerly 4NT), Michael J.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Mefford's ANSI.COM, Jason Hood's ANSICON and Maximus5's ConEmu enabled ANSI escape sequences.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Software such as the Python colorama package or Cygwin modified text in-process as it was sent to the console, extracting the ANSI Escape sequences and emulating them with Windows calls.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In 2016, Microsoft released the Windows 10 version 1511 update which unexpectedly implemented support for ANSI escape sequences, over three decades after the debut of Windows.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This was done alongside Windows Subsystem for Linux, apparently to allow Unix-like terminal-based software to use the Windows Console.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Windows PowerShell 5.1 enabled this by default, and PowerShell 6 made it possible to embed the necessary ESC character into a string with `e.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Windows Terminal, introduced in 2019, supports the sequences by default.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Since Windows 11 22H2 and Windows Terminal 1.15, Windows Terminal replaces Windows Console as the default.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Almost all users assume some functions of some single-byte characters.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The general format for an ANSI-compliant escape sequence is defined by ANSI X3.41 (equivalent to ECMA-35 or ISO/IEC 2022).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The escape sequences consist only of bytes in the range 0x20—0x7F (all the non-control ASCII characters), and can be parsed without looking ahead.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The behavior when a control character, a byte with the high bit set, or a byte that is not part of any valid sequence is encountered before the end is undefined.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x40 to 0x5F, the escape sequence is of type `Fe`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Its interpretation is delegated to the applicable C1 control code standard.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Accordingly, all escape sequences corresponding to C1 control codes from ANSI X3.64 / ECMA-48 follow this format.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The standard says that, in 8-bit environments, the control functions corresponding to type `Fe` escape sequences (those from the set of C1 control codes) can be represented as single bytes in the 0x80–0x9F range.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This is possible in character encodings conforming to the provisions for an 8-bit code made in ISO 2022, such as the ISO 8859 series.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] However, in character encodings used on modern devices such as UTF-8 or CP-1252, those codes are often used for other purposes, so only the 2-byte sequence is typically used.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] In the case of UTF-8, representing a C1 control code via the C1 Controls and Latin-1 Supplement block results in a different two-byte code (e.g.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] 0xC2,0x8E for U+008E), but no space is saved this way.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] All common sequences just use the parameters as a series of semicolon-separated numbers such as `1;2;3`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Missing numbers are treated as `0` (`1;;3` acts like the middle number is `0`, and no parameters at all in `ESC[m` acts like a `0` reset code).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some sequences (such as CUU) treat `0` as `1` in order to make missing parameters useful.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] A subset of arrangements was declared "private" so that terminal manufacturers could insert their own sequences without conflicting with the standard.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Sequences containing the parameter bytes `<=>?` or the final bytes 0x70–0x7E (`p–z{|}~`) are private.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The behavior of the terminal is undefined in the case where a CSI sequence contains any character outside of the range 0x20–0x7E.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] These illegal characters are either C0 control characters (the range 0–0x1F), DEL (0x7F), or bytes with the high bit set.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Possible responses are to ignore the byte, to process it immediately, and furthermore whether to continue with the CSI sequence, to abort it immediately, or to ignore the rest of it.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The control sequence `CSI *n* m`, named Select Graphic Rendition (SGR), sets display attributes.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Several attributes can be set in the same sequence, separated by semicolons.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Each display attribute remains in effect until a following occurrence of SGR resets it.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If no codes are given, `CSI m` is treated as `CSI 0 m` (reset / normal).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The original specification only had 8 colors, and just gave them names.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The SGR parameters 30–37 selected the foreground color, while 40–47 selected the background.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Quite a few terminals implemented "bold" (SGR code 1) as a brighter color rather than a different font, thus providing 8 additional foreground colors.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Usually you could not get these as background colors, though sometimes inverse video (SGR code 7) would allow that.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Examples: to get black letters on white background use `ESC[30;47m`, to get red use `ESC[31m`, to get bright red use `ESC[1;31m`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] To reset colors to their defaults, use `ESC[39;49m` (not supported on some terminals), or reset all attributes with `ESC[0m`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Later terminals added the ability to directly specify the "bright" colors with 90–97 and 100–107.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The chart below shows a few examples of how classical standards and modern terminal emulators translate the 4-bit color codes into 24-bit color codes.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The colors displayed by these values vary across terminal/emulator implementations as the recognized ECMA-48 and ITU's T.416 specifications do not define a specific color palette for this lookup table.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] While it is common to use the above formula for the color palette, in particular the algorithm and choice of colors for the 16-231 cube values differs between implementations.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The color palette and algorithm used by XTerm is specified below as a sample.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] There has also been a similar but incompatible 88-color encoding using the same escape sequence, seen in `rxvt` and `xterm-88color`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As "true color" graphic cards with 16 to 24 bits of color became common, applications began to support 24-bit colors.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Terminal emulators supporting setting 24-bit foreground and background colors with escape sequences include Xterm, KDE's Konsole, and iTerm, as well as all libvte based terminals, including GNOME Terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This syntax, initially implemented in XTerm, is based on a reading of the ISO/IEC 8613-6 specification, specifically that SGR 38 / SGR 48 followed by the parameter "2" can specify a "direct color" in RGB space..
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As the first widely-used implementation, this specification of RGB values using semicolon separators is widely supported by terminal emulators that include 24-bit color support.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] As with the 8-bit color codes, there is a very similar specification of 24-bit color in the ITU's T.416 Open Document Architecture (ODA) and interchange format: Character content architectures, which was adopted as ISO/IEC 8613-6 but ended up as a commercial failure.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] where `Color-Space` indicates the Color-Space associated with the given tolerance: `0` for CIELUV or `1` for CIELAB.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The semicolon-based RGB specification is the most widely supported, but both it and the RGB variant of ITU T.416 are supported by many terminal emulators.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This system, although poorly documented, became widespread enough for Fedora and RHEL to consider using it as a simpler and more universal detection mechanism compared to querying the now-updated libraries.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some terminal emulators (urxvt, Konsole) set `$COLORFGBG` to report the color scheme of the terminal (mainly light vs. dark background).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This behavior originated in S-Lang and is used by vim.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Gnome-terminal refuses to add this behavior, as the syntax for the value is not agreed upon, the value cannot be changed upon a runtime change of the palette, and more "proper" xterm OSC 4/10/11 sequences already exist.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] It has become conventional to use the `NO_COLOR` environment variable to disable colors unconditionally.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Most Operating System Command sequences were defined by Xterm, but many are also supported by other terminal emulators.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For historical reasons, Xterm can end the command with `BEL` (0x07) as well as the standard `ST` (0x9C or 0x1B 0x5C).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For example, Xterm allows the icon name and window title to be set by `ESC ]0;this is the title BEL`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] A non-xterm extension is the hyperlink, `ESC ]8;;link ST` from 2017, used by VTE, iTerm2, and mintty, among others.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The Linux console uses `ESC ] P n rr gg bb` to change the palette, which, if hard-coded into an application, may hang other terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] However, appending `ST` will be ignored by Linux and form a proper, ignorable sequence for other terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x60—0x7E, the escape sequence is of type `Fs`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This type is used for control functions individually registered with the ISO-IR registry.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] A table of these is listed under ISO/IEC 2022.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x30—0x3F, the escape sequence is of type `Fp`, which is set apart for up to sixteen private-use control functions.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the `ESC` is followed by a byte in the range 0x20—0x2F, the escape sequence is of type `nF`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Said byte is followed by any number of additional bytes in this range, and then a byte in the range 0x30-0x7E.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] These escape sequences are further subcategorised by the low two bits of the first byte, e.g.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] "type `2F`" for sequences where the first byte is 0x22; and by whether the final byte is in the range 0x30—0x3F indicating private use (e.g.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Most of the `nFt` sequences are for changing the current character set, and are listed in ISO/IEC 2022.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the first byte is '#' the public sequences are reserved for additional ISO-IR registered individual control functions.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] No such sequences are presently registered.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Type `3Fp` sequences (which includes ones starting with '#') are available for private-use control functions.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] `CSI 2 J` — This clears the screen and, on some devices, locates the cursor to the y,x position 1,1 (upper left corner).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The green may be a dark, dull green, so you may wish to enable Bold with the sequence `CSI 1 m` which would make it bright green, or combined as `CSI 32 ; 1 m`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some implementations use the Bold state to make the character Bright.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] `CSI 0 ; 6 8 ; "DIR" ; 13 p` — This reassigns the key F10 to send to the keyboard buffer the string "DIR" and ENTER, which in the DOS command line would display the contents of the current directory.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] (MS-DOS ANSI.SYS only) This was sometimes used for ANSI bombs.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This is a private-use code (as indicated by the letter p), using a non-standard extension to include a string-valued parameter.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Following the letter of the standard would consider the sequence to end at the letter D.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] `CSI s` — This saves the cursor position.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Using the sequence `CSI u` will restore it to the position.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Say the current cursor position is 7(y) and 10(x).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The sequence `CSI s` will save those two numbers.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Now you can move to a different cursor position, such as 20(y) and 3(x), using the sequence `CSI 20 ; 3 H` or `CSI 20 ; 3 f`.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Now if you use the sequence CSI u the cursor position will return to 7(y) and 10(x).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Some terminals require the DEC sequences `ESC 7` / `ESC 8` instead which is more widely supported.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] ANSI escape codes are often used in UNIX and UNIX-like terminals to provide syntax highlighting.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For example, on compatible terminals, the following *list* command color-codes file and directory names by type.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Users can employ escape codes in their scripts by including them as part of *standard output* or *standard error*.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For example, the following GNU *sed* command embellishes the output of the *make* command by displaying lines containing words starting with "WARN" in reverse video and words starting with "ERR" in bright yellow on a dark red background (letter case is ignored).
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The representations of the codes are highlighted.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The following Bash function flashes the terminal (by alternately sending reverse and normal video mode codes) until the user presses a key.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] It can be used to alert a programmer when a lengthy command terminates, such as with `make ; flasher` .
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The following command will reset the console, similar to the command `reset` on modern Linux systems; however it should work even on older Linux systems and on other (non-Linux) UNIX variants.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] This following program creates a table of numbers from 0 to 109, each of which is displayed in the format specified by the Select Graphic Rendition escape sequence using that number as the graphic rendition code.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Pressing special keys on the keyboard, as well as outputting many xterm CSI, DCS, or OSC sequences, often produces a CSI, DCS, or OSC sequence, sent from the terminal to the computer as though the user typed it.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] When typing input on a terminal keypresses outside the normal main alphanumeric keyboard area can be sent to the host as ANSI sequences.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] For keys that have an equivalent output function, such as the cursor keys, these often mirror the output sequences.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] However, for most keypresses there isn't an equivalent output sequence to use.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] There are several encoding schemes, and unfortunately most terminals mix sequences from different schemes, so host software has to be able to deal with input sequences using any scheme.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] To complicate the matter, the VT terminals themselves have two schemes of input, *normal mode* and *application mode* that can be switched by the application.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the terminating character is '~', the first number must be present and is a keycode number, the second number is an optional modifier value.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] If the terminating character is a letter, the letter is the keycode value, and the optional number is the modifier value.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The modifier value defaults to 1, and after subtracting 1 is a bitmap of modifier keys being pressed: Meta+Ctrl+Alt+⇧ Shift.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] `<esc>[A` to `<esc>[D` are the same as the ANSI output sequences.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] The `<modifier>` is normally omitted if no modifier keys are pressed, but most implementations always emit the `<modifier>` for F1–F4.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Xterm has a comprehensive documentation page on the various function-key and mouse input sequence schemes from DEC's VT terminals and various other terminals it emulates.
[src:rich-terminal/ansi-escape-code] Thomas Dickey has added a lot of support to it over time; he also maintains a list of default keys used by other terminal emulators for comparison.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A **computer terminal** is an electronic or electromechanical hardware device that can be used for entering data into, and transcribing data from, a computer or a computing system.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Most early computers only had a front panel to input or display bits and had to be connected to a terminal to print or input text through a keyboard.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Teleprinters were used as early-day hard-copy terminals and predated the use of a computer screen by decades.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The computer would typically transmit a line of data which would be printed on paper, and accept a line of data from a keyboard over a serial or other interface.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Early terminals were inexpensive devices but very slow compared to punched cards or paper tape for input; with the advent of time-sharing systems, terminals slowly pushed these older forms of interaction from the industry.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Related developments were the improvement of terminal technology and the introduction of inexpensive video displays.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Early Teletypes only printed out with a communications speed of only 75 baud or ten 5-bit characters per second, and by the 1970s speeds of video terminals had improved to 2400 bit/s or 9600 bit/s.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Similarly, the speed of remote batch terminals had improved to 4800 bit/s at the beginning of the decade and 19.6 kbps by the end of the decade, with higher speeds possible on more expensive terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The function of a terminal is typically confined to transcription and input of data; a device with significant local, programmable data-processing capability may be called a "smart terminal" or fat client.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A terminal that depends on the host computer for its processing power is called a "dumb terminal" or a thin client.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The use of terminals decreased over time as computing shifted from command line interface (CLI) to graphical user interface (GUI) and from time-sharing on large computers to personal computers and handheld devices.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Today, users generally interact with a server over high-speed networks using a Web browser and other network-enabled GUI applications.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Today, a terminal emulator application provides the capabilities of a physical terminal – allowing interaction with the operating system shell and other CLI applications.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Examples of modern terminal emulators include xterm, GNOME Console, Konsole, Terminal, Windows Terminal, and PuTTY.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The console of Konrad Zuse's Z3 had a keyboard in 1941, as did the Z4 in 1942–1945.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] However, these consoles could only be used to enter numeric inputs and were thus analogous to those of calculating machines; programs, commands, and other data were entered via paper tape.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Both machines had a row of display lamps for results.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In 1956, the Whirlwind Mark I computer became the first computer equipped with a keyboard-printer combination with which to support direct input of data and commands and output of results.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] That device was a Friden Flexowriter, which would continue to serve this purpose on many other early computers well into the 1960s.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Some terminals, such as the ASR Teletype models, included a paper tape reader and punch which could record output such as a program listing.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The data on the tape could be re-entered into the computer using the tape reader on the teletype, or printed to paper.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Teletypes used the current loop interface that was already used in telegraphy.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A less expensive Read Only (RO) configuration was available for the Teletype.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Custom-designs keyboard/printer terminals that came later included the IBM 2741 (1965) and the DECwriter (1970).
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Respective top speeds of teletypes, IBM 2741 and the LA30 (an early DECwriter) were 10, 15 and 30 characters per second.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Although at that time "paper was king" the speed of interaction was relatively limited.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The DECwriter was the last major printing-terminal product.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] It faded away after 1980 under pressure from video display units (VDUs), with the last revision (the DECwriter IV of 1982) abandoning the classic teletypewriter form for one more resembling a desktop printer.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Printing terminals required that the print mechanism be away from the paper after a pause in the print flow, to allow an interactively typing user to see what they had just typed and make corrections, or to read a prompt string.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] As a dot-matrix printer, the DECwriter family would move the print head sideways after each pause, returning to the last print position when the next character came from the remote computer (or local echo).
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A **video display unit** (VDU) displays information on a screen rather than printing text to paper and typically uses a cathode-ray tube (CRT).
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Two early landmarks in the development of the VDU were the Univac Uniscope and the IBM 2260, both in 1964.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] These were block-mode terminals designed to display a page at a time, using proprietary protocols; in contrast to character-mode devices, they enter data from the keyboard into a display buffer rather than transmitting them immediately.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In contrast to later character-mode devices, the Uniscope used synchronous serial communication over an EIA RS-232 interface to communicate between the multiplexer and the host, while the 2260 used either a channel connection or asynchronous serial communication between the 2848 and the host.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The 2265, related to the 2260, also used asynchronous serial communication.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The Datapoint 3300 from Computer Terminal Corporation, announced in 1967 and shipped in 1969, was a character-mode device that emulated a Model 33 Teletype.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] This reflects the fact that early character-mode terminals were often deployed to replace teletype machines as a way to reduce operating costs.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The next generation of VDUs went beyond teletype emulation with an addressable cursor that gave them the ability to paint two-dimensional displays on the screen.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Very early VDUs with cursor addressibility included the VT05 and the Hazeltine 2000 operating in character mode, both from 1970.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Despite this capability, early devices of this type were often called "Glass TTYs".
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Later, the term "glass TTY" tended to be restrospectively narrowed to devices without full cursor addressibility.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The classic era of the VDU began in the early 1970s and was closely intertwined with the rise of time sharing computers.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Important early products were the ADM-3A, VT52, and VT100.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] These devices used no complicated CPU, instead relying on individual logic gates, LSI chips, or microprocessors such as the Intel 8080.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] This made them inexpensive and they quickly became extremely popular input-output devices on many types of computer system, often replacing earlier and more expensive printing terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The experimental era of serial VDUs culminated with the VT100 in 1978.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The great majority of terminals were monochrome, manufacturers variously offering green, white or amber and sometimes blue screen phosphors.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] (Amber was claimed to reduce eye strain).
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Terminals with modest color capability were also available but not widely used; for example, a color version of the popular Wyse WY50, the WY350, offered 64 shades on each character cell.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] VDUs were eventually displaced from most applications by networked personal computers, at first slowly after 1985 and with increasing speed in the 1990s.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] However, they had a lasting influence on PCs.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The keyboard layout of the VT220 terminal strongly influenced the Model M shipped on IBM PCs from 1985, and through it all later computer keyboards.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Although flat-panel displays were available since the 1950s, cathode-ray tubes continued to dominate the market until the personal computer had made serious inroads into the display terminal market.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] By the time cathode-ray tubes on PCs were replaced by flatscreens after the year 2000, the hardware computer terminal was nearly obsolete.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A **character-oriented terminal** is a type of computer terminal that communicates with its host one character at a time, as opposed to a block-oriented terminal that communicates in blocks of data.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] It is the most common type of data terminal, because it is easy to implement and program.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Connection to the mainframe computer or terminal server is achieved via RS-232 serial links, Ethernet or other proprietary protocols.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Character-oriented terminals can be "dumb" or "smart".
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Dumb terminals are those that can interpret a limited number of control codes (CR, LF, etc.) but do not have the ability to process special escape sequences that perform functions such as clearing a line, clearing the screen, or controlling cursor position.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In this context dumb terminals are sometimes dubbed *glass Teletypes*, for they essentially have the same limited functionality as does a mechanical Teletype.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] This type of dumb terminal is still supported on modern Unix-like systems by setting the environment variable `TERM` to `dumb`.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Smart or intelligent terminals are those that also have the ability to process escape sequences, in particular the VT52, VT100 or ANSI escape sequences.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A **text terminal**, or often just *terminal* (sometimes *text console*) is a serial computer interface for text entry and display.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Information is presented as an array of pre-selected formed characters.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] When such devices use a video display such as a cathode-ray tube, they are called a "video display unit" or "visual display unit" (VDU) or "video display terminal" (VDT).
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The system console is often a text terminal used to operate a computer.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Modern computers have a built-in keyboard and display for the console.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Some Unix-like operating systems such as Linux and FreeBSD have virtual consoles to provide several text terminals on a single computer.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The fundamental type of application running on a text terminal is a command-line interpreter or *shell*, which prompts for commands from the user and executes each command after a press of Return.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] This includes Unix shells and some interactive programming environments.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In a shell, most of the commands are small applications themselves.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Another important application type is that of the text editor.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A text editor typically occupies the full area of display, displays one or more text documents, and allows the user to edit the documents.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The text editor has, for many uses, been replaced by the word processor, which usually provides rich formatting features that the text editor lacks.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The first word processors used text to communicate the structure of the document, but later word processors operate in a graphical environment and provide a WYSIWYG simulation of the formatted output.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] However, text editors are still used for documents containing markup such as DocBook or LaTeX.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Programs such as Telix and Minicom control a modem and the local terminal to let the user interact with remote servers.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] On the Internet, telnet and ssh work similarly.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In the simplest form, a text terminal is like a file.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Writing to the file displays the text and reading from the file produces what the user enters.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In Unix-like operating systems, there are several character special files that correspond to available text terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] For other operations, there are special escape sequences, control characters and `termios` functions that a program can use, most easily via a library such as *ncurses*.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] For more complex operations, the programs can use terminal specific *ioctl* system calls.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] For an application, the simplest way to use a terminal is to simply write and read text strings to and from it sequentially.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The output text is scrolled, so that only the last several lines (typically 24) are visible.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Unix systems typically buffer the input text until the Enter key is pressed, so the application receives a ready string of text.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In this mode, the application need not know much about the terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] For many interactive applications this is not sufficient.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] One of the common enhancements is *command-line editing* (assisted with such libraries as readline); it also may give access to command history.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] This is very helpful for various interactive command-line interpreters.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Even more advanced interactivity is provided with *full-screen* applications.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Those applications completely control the screen layout; also they respond to key-pressing immediately.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] This mode is very useful for text editors, file managers and web browsers.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In addition, such programs control the color and brightness of text on the screen, and decorate it with underline, blinking and special characters (e.g. box-drawing characters).
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The great problem here is that there are many different terminals and terminal emulators, each with its own set of escape sequences.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In order to overcome this, special libraries (such as curses) have been created, together with terminal description databases, such as Termcap and Terminfo.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A **block-oriented terminal** or **block mode terminal** is a type of computer terminal that communicates with its host in blocks of data, as opposed to a character-oriented terminal that communicates with its host one character at a time.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A block-oriented terminal may be card-oriented, display-oriented, keyboard-display, keyboard-printer, printer or some combination.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The IBM 3270 is perhaps the most familiar implementation of a block-oriented display terminal, but most mainframe computer manufacturers and several other companies produced them.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The description below is in terms of the 3270, but similar considerations apply to other types.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Block-oriented terminals typically incorporate a buffer which stores one screen or more of data, and also stores data attributes, not only indicating appearance (color, brightness, blinking, etc.) but also marking the data as being enterable by the terminal operator vs.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] *protected* against entry, as allowing the entry of only numeric information vs. allowing any characters, etc.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In a typical application the host sends the terminal a preformatted panel containing both static data and fields into which data may be entered.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The terminal operator keys data, such as updates in a database entry, into the appropriate fields.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] When entry is complete (or ENTER or PF key pressed on 3270s), a block of data, usually just the data entered by the operator (modified data), is sent to the host in one transmission.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The 3270 terminal buffer (at the device) could be updated on a single character basis, if necessary, because of the existence of a "set buffer address order" (SBA), that usually preceded any data to be written/overwritten within the buffer.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A complete buffer could also be read or replaced using the `READ BUFFER` command or `WRITE` command (unformatted or formatted in the case of the 3270).
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Block-oriented terminals cause less system load on the host and less network traffic than character-oriented terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] They also appear more responsive to the user, especially over slow connections, since editing within a field is done locally rather than depending on echoing from the host system.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Early terminals had limited editing capabilities – 3270 terminals, for example, only could check entries as valid numerics.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Subsequent "smart" or "intelligent" terminals incorporated microprocessors and supported more local processing.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Programmers of block-oriented terminals often used the technique of storing *context* information for the transaction in progress on the screen, possibly in a hidden field, rather than depending on a running program to keep track of status.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] This was the precursor of the HTML technique of storing context in the URL as data to be passed as arguments to a CGI program.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Programmers might "protect" the last screen position to prevent inadvertent wrap.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Likewise a protected field following an enterable field might lock the keyboard and sound an audible alarm if the operator attempted to enter more data into the field than allowed.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A **graphical terminal** can display images as well as text.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Graphical terminals are divided into vector-mode terminals, and raster mode.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A vector-mode display directly draws lines on the face of a cathode-ray tube under control of the host computer system.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The lines are continuously formed, but since the speed of electronics is limited, the number of concurrent lines that can be displayed at one time is limited.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Vector-mode displays were historically important but are no longer used.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Practically all modern graphic displays are raster-mode, descended from the picture scanning techniques used for television, in which the visual elements are a rectangular array of pixels.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Since the raster image is only perceptible to the human eye as a whole for a very short time, the raster must be refreshed many times per second to give the appearance of a persistent display.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The electronic demands of refreshing display memory meant that graphic terminals were developed much later than text terminals, and initially cost much more.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Most terminals today are graphical; that is, they can show images on the screen.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The modern term for graphical terminal is "thin client".
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A thin client typically uses a protocol such as X11 for Unix terminals, or RDP for Microsoft Windows.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The bandwidth needed depends on the protocol used, the resolution, and the color depth.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Modern graphic terminals allow display of images in color, and of text in varying sizes, colors, and fonts (type faces).
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In the early 1990s, an industry consortium attempted to define a standard, AlphaWindows, that would allow a single CRT screen to implement multiple windows, each of which was to behave as a distinct terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Unfortunately, like I2O, this suffered from being run as a closed standard: non-members were unable to obtain even minimal information and there was no realistic way a small company or independent developer could join the consortium.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] An **intelligent terminal** does its own processing, usually implying a microprocessor is built in, but not all terminals with microprocessors did any real processing of input: the main computer to which it was attached would have to respond quickly to each keystroke.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The term "intelligent" in this context dates from 1969.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Notable examples include the IBM 2250, predecessor to the IBM 3250 and IBM 5080, and IBM 2260, predecessor to the IBM 3270, introduced with System/360 in 1964.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Most terminals were connected to minicomputers or mainframe computers and often had a green or amber screen.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Typically terminals communicate with the computer via a serial port via a null modem cable, often using an EIA RS-232 or RS-422 or RS-423 or a current loop serial interface.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In fact, the instruction design for the Intel 8008 was originally conceived at Computer Terminal Corporation as the processor for the Datapoint 2200.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Most terminals in the early 1980s, such as ADM-3A, TVI912, Data General D2, DEC VT52, despite the introduction of ANSI terminals in 1978, were essentially "dumb" terminals, although some of them (such as the later ADM and TVI models) did have a primitive block-send capability.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The advance in microprocessors and lower memory costs made it possible for the terminal to handle editing operations such as inserting characters within a field that may have previously required a full screen-full of characters to be re-sent from the computer, possibly over a slow modem line.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Around the mid-1980s most intelligent terminals, costing less than most dumb terminals would have a few years earlier, could provide enough user-friendly local editing of data and send the completed form to the main computer.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Providing even more processing possibilities, workstations such as the TeleVideo TS-800 could run CP/M-86, blurring the distinction between terminal and Personal Computer.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Another of the motivations for development of the microprocessor was to simplify and reduce the electronics required in a terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] That also made it practicable to load several "personalities" into a single terminal, so a Qume QVT-102 could emulate many popular terminals of the day, and so be sold into organizations that did not wish to make any software changes.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The ANSI X3.64 escape code standard produced uniformity to some extent, but significant differences remained.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In the 21st century, the term *Intelligent Terminal* can now refer to a retail Point of Sale computer.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Even though the early IBM PC looked somewhat like a terminal with a green monochrome monitor, it is not classified a terminal since it provides local computing instead of interacting with a server at a character level.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] With terminal emulator software, a PC can, however, provide the function of a terminal to interact with a mainframe or minicomputer.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Eventually, personal computers greatly reduced market demand for conventional terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In and around the 1990s, *thin client* and X terminal technology combined the relatively economical local processing power with central, shared computer facilities to leverage advantages of terminals over personal computers.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In a GUI environment, such as the X Window System, the display can show multiple programs – each in its own window – rather than a single stream of text associated with a single program.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] As a terminal emulator runs in a GUI environment to provide command-line access, it alleviates the need for a physical terminal and allows for multiple windows running separate emulators.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] It is a physical device consisting of a keyboard and a printer or screen, and traditionally is a text terminal, but may also be a graphical terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Another, older, meaning of system console, computer console, **hardware console**, operator's console or simply console is a hardware component used by an operator to control the hardware, typically some combination of front panel, keyboard/printer and keyboard/display.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Some early operating systems supported either a single keyboard/print or keyboard/display device for controlling the OS.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Some also supported a single alternate console, and some supported a hardcopy console for retaining a record of commands, responses and other console messages.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] However, in the late 1960s it became common for operating systems to support many more consoles than 3, and operating systems began appearing in which the console was simply any terminal with a privileged user logged on.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] On early minicomputers, the console was a **serial console**, an RS-232 serial link to a terminal such as a ASR-33 or, later, a terminal from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), e.g., DECWriter, VT100.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] This terminal was usually kept in a secured room since it could be used for certain privileged functions such as halting the system or selecting which media to boot from.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Large midrange systems, e.g. those from Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and IBM, still use serial consoles.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In larger installations, the console ports are attached to multiplexers or network-connected multiport serial servers that let an operator connect a terminal to any of the attached servers.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Today, serial consoles are often used for accessing headless systems, usually with a terminal emulator running on a laptop.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Also, routers, enterprise network switches and other telecommunication equipment have RS-232 serial console ports.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] On PCs and workstations, the computer's attached keyboard and monitor have the equivalent function.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Since the monitor cable carries video signals, it cannot be extended very far.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Often, installations with many servers therefore use keyboard/video multiplexers (KVM switches) and possibly video amplifiers to centralize console access.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In recent years, KVM/IP devices have become available that allow a remote computer to view the video output and send keyboard input via any TCP/IP network and therefore the Internet.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Some PC BIOSes, especially in servers, also support serial consoles, giving access to the BIOS through a serial port so that the simpler and cheaper serial console infrastructure can be used.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Even where BIOS support is lacking, some operating systems, e.g.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] FreeBSD and Linux, can be configured for serial console operation either during bootup, or after startup.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Starting with the IBM 9672, IBM large systems have used a Hardware Management Console (HMC), consisting of a PC and a specialized application, instead of a 3270 or serial link.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Other IBM product lines also use an HMC, e.g., System p.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] It is usually possible to log in from the console.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Depending on configuration, the operating system may treat a login session from the console as being more trustworthy than a login session from other sources.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] A terminal emulator is a piece of software that emulates a text terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In the past, before the widespread use of local area networks and broadband internet access, many computers would use a serial access program to communicate with other computers via telephone line or serial device.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] When the first Macintosh was released, a program called MacTerminal was used to communicate with many computers, including the IBM PC.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] The terminal emulators on most Unix-like systems—such as, for example, gnome-terminal, Konsole, QTerminal, xterm, and Terminal.app—do emulate physical terminals including support for escape sequences; e.g., xterm can emulate the VT220 and Tektronix 4010 hardware terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] There is a distinction between the return and the ↵ Enter keys.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In some multiple-mode terminals, that can switch between modes, pressing the ↵ Enter key when *not* in block mode does not do the same thing as pressing the return key.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Whilst the return key will cause an input line to be sent to the host in line-at-a-time mode, the ↵ Enter key will rather cause the terminal to transmit the contents of the character row where the cursor is currently positioned to the host, host-issued prompts and all.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Some block-mode terminals have both an ↵ Enter and local cursor moving keys such as Return and New Line.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Different computer operating systems require different degrees of mode support when terminals are used as computer terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] Most usually, and especially so that the host system can support non-canonical input mode, terminals for POSIX-compliant systems are always in character-at-a-time mode.
[src:rich-terminal/computer-terminal] In contrast, IBM 3270 terminals connected to MVS systems are always required to be in block mode.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] In computing, an **escape sequence** is a sequence of characters that has a special semantic meaning based on an established convention that specifies an escape character prefix in addition to the syntax of the rest of the text of a sequence.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] A convention can define any particular character code as a sequence prefix.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Some conventions use a normal, printable character such as backslash (\) or ampersand (&).
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Others use a non-printable (a.k.a. control) character such as ASCII *escape*.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Escape sequences date back at least to the 1874 Baudot code.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] A common use of an escape sequence is to remove control characters from a data stream so that it does not cause its control function by mistake.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] The control character is replaced with an escape character and one or more other subsequent characters.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] After escaping the normal context in which the control character would have caused an action, the sequence is replaced by the removed character.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] To transmit the escape character itself, two copies are sent.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] An escape sequence is often used in character and string literals, to express characters that are not printable or clash with the syntax of characters or strings.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] For example, control characters might not be allowed in a source file or may have undesirable side-effects if typed into a command.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] A feature of C and many programming languages influenced by it is that the beginning of an escape sequence in such text literals is marked by a backslash (`\`).
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Common examples of these C-style escape sequences include `\r`, `\n` and `\t` for the carriage return, newline, and tab characters, respectively.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] To account for the fact that using a printable character for escape causes that character to lose its normal meaning, a sequence of two backslash characters (`\\`) is provided to express a single backslash.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] There is also an escape sequence that expresses any character by its ASCII-code value.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] For example, the backslash can be expressed as either `\x5c` or `\134`, which specify the character code value in hexadecimal and octal notations, respectively.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Likewise, the lowercase *e* can be expressed as `\145` and the digit 7 as `\067`.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] A backslash immediately followed by a newline (which is necessarily outside of a string literal) does not mark an escape sequence.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Instead, it can be thought of as meaning "Disregard the newline": the C preprocessor joins the line with the subsequent line.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] In C and many related languages, the escape character is the backslash (`\`).
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] The single quotation mark character can be coded as `'\''` since `'''` is not valid.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] As a string literal is delimited by double-quotes (`"`) the content cannot contain a double-quote unless it is escaped (`"\""`) or via a sequence that specifies the code of the double-quote character (`\x22`).
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Alternatively, the following uses "\x" to indicate the subsequent two characters are hexadecimal digits; "22" being the hexadecimal ASCII value for double-quote.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] C, C++, Java, and Ruby allow the same two backslash escape styles.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] PostScript and rich text format (RTF) also use backslash escapes.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] The quoted-printable encoding uses the equals sign as an escape character.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] URL and URI use percent-encoding to quote characters with a special meaning, as for non-ASCII characters.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] The VT52 terminal used simple digraph commands like escape-A.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Without the escape character prefix, `A` simply meant the letter `A`, but as part of the escape sequence `escape-A`, it had a different meaning.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] It was not a straightforward control language encoded as substitution.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] The later VT100 terminal implemented the more sophisticated ANSI escape sequences standard (now ECMA-48) for functions such as controlling cursor movement, character set, and display enhancements.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] The HP 2640 series had perhaps the most elaborate escape sequences for block and character modes, programming keys and their soft labels, graphics vectors, and even saving data to tape or disk files.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] In Windows (and MS-DOS), a utility, ANSI.SYS, can be used to enable ANSI escape sequence support.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] In DOS via `$e` in the PROMPT command), and in 16-bit Windows via a command window.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the ANSI escape sequences are generally supported by the shell.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] The rise of GUI applications has reduced the use of escape sequences, yet the ability to provide full-screen, text-based applications is still available.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] A control sequence is a sequence of characters that changes the state of a computer peripheral instead of conveying the normal information that the characters represent.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] In an ANSI escape sequence, the escape sequence prefix, called control sequence introducer, can be either ASCII ESC (decimal 27) followed by `[` or CSI (decimal 155).
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Escape sequences in communications are commonly used when a computer and a peripheral have only a single channel through which to send information back and forth (so escape sequences are an example of in-band signaling).
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] They were common when most dumb terminals used ASCII with 7 data bits for communication, and sometimes would be used to switch to a different character set for "foreign" or graphics characters that would otherwise been restricted by the 128 codes available in 7 data bits.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Even relatively "dumb" terminals responded to some escape sequences, including the original mechanical Teletype printers (on which "glass Teletypes" or VDUs were based) responded to characters 27 and 31 to alternate between letters and figures modes.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Many computer keyboards have an Esc key (where *Esc* is short for *escape*) even though it is generally not used for entering an escape sequence.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] The vi text editor uses the key to exit from input mode.
[src:rich-terminal/escape-sequence] Some application use the key to cancel an operation or navigate up a level of a nested context.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Rich is a Python library for writing *rich* text (with color and style) to the terminal, and for displaying advanced content such as tables, markdown, and syntax highlighted code.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Use Rich to make your command line applications visually appealing and present data in a more readable way.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Rich can also be a useful debugging aid by pretty printing and syntax highlighting data structures.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Rich works with macOS, Linux and Windows.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] On Windows both the (ancient) cmd.exe terminal is supported and the new Windows Terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] The latter has much improved support for color and style.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] PyCharm users will need to enable “emulate terminal” in output console option in run/debug configuration to see styled output.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Add the `-U` switch to update to the current version, if Rich is already installed.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] The quickest way to get up and running with Rich is to import the alternative `print` function which takes the same arguments as the built-in `print` and may be used as a drop-in replacement.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] You can then print strings or objects to the terminal in the usual way.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Rich will do some basic syntax highlighting and format data structures to make them easier to read.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Strings may contain Console Markup which can be used to insert color and styles in to the output.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Continue reading to learn about the more advanced features of Rich.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Rich may be installed in the REPL so that Python data structures are automatically pretty printed with syntax highlighting.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] You can also use this feature to try out Rich *renderables*.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Read on to learn more about Rich renderables.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Rich also includes an IPython extension that will do this same pretty install + pretty tracebacks.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] You can also have it load by default by adding *“rich”* to the `c.InteractiveShellApp.extension` variable in IPython Configuration.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] Rich has an `inspect()` function which can generate a report on any Python object.
[src:rich-terminal/introduction] It is a fantastic debug aid, and a good example of the output that Rich can generate.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Rich supports a simple markup which you can use to insert color and styles virtually everywhere Rich would accept a string (e.g.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Console markup uses a syntax inspired by bbcode.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] If you write the style (see Styles) in square brackets, e.g.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] `[bold red]`, that style will apply until it is *closed* with a corresponding `[/bold red]`.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] If you don’t close a style, it will apply until the end of the string.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Which is sometimes convenient if you want to style a single line.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] There is a shorthand for closing a style.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] If you omit the style name from the closing tag, Rich will close the last style.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] These markup tags may be use in combination with each other and don’t need to be strictly nested.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Console markup can output hyperlinks with the following syntax: `[link=URL]text[/link]`.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] If your terminal software supports hyperlinks, you will be able to click the word “blog” which will typically open a browser.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] If your terminal doesn’t support hyperlinks, you will see the text but it won’t be clickable.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Occasionally you may want to print something that Rich would interpret as markup.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] You can *escape* a tag by preceding it with a backslash.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Without the backslash, Rich will assume that `[bar]` is a tag and remove it from the output if there is no “bar” style.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] If you want to prevent the backslash from escaping the tag and output a literal backslash before a tag you can enter two backslashes.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] The function `escape()` will handle escaping of text for you.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Escaping is important if you construct console markup dynamically, with `str.format` or f strings (for example).
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Without escaping it may be possible to inject tags where you don’t want them.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Calling `greet("Will")` will print a greeting, but if you were to call `greet("[blink]Gotcha![/blink]")` then you will also get blinking text, which may not be desirable.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] If you add an *emoji code* to markup it will be replaced with the equivalent unicode character.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] An emoji code consists of the name of the emoji surrounded be colons (:).
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Some emojis have two variants, the “emoji” variant displays in full color, and the “text” variant displays in monochrome (whatever your default colors are set to).
[src:rich-terminal/markup] You can specify the variant you want by adding either *“-emoji”* or *“-text”* to the emoji code.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] By default, Rich will render console markup when you explicitly pass a string to `print()` or implicitly when you embed a string in another renderable object such as `Table` or `Panel`.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] Console markup is convenient, but you may wish to disable it if the syntax clashes with the string you want to print.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] You can do this by setting `markup=False` on the `print()` method or on the `Console` constructor.
[src:rich-terminal/markup] You can convert a string to styled text by calling `from_markup()`, which returns a `Text` instance you can print or add more styles to.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] A **terminal emulator**, or **terminal application**, is a computer program that emulates a video terminal within another display architecture.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Though typically synonymous with a shell or text terminal, the term *terminal* covers all remote terminals, including graphical interfaces.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] A terminal emulator inside a graphical user interface is often called a **terminal window**.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] A terminal window allows the user access to a text terminal and all its applications such as command-line interfaces (CLI) and text user interface (TUI) applications.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] These may be running either on the same machine or on a different one via telnet, ssh, dial-up, or over a direct serial connection.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] On Unix-like operating systems, it is common to have one or more terminal windows connected to the local machine.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Terminals usually support a set of escape sequences for controlling color, cursor position, etc.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Examples include the family of terminal control sequence standards that includes ECMA-48, ANSI X3.64, and ISO/IEC 6429.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] In the early days of computing, with the advent of interactive computing, the prevailing model involved a central computer connected to multiple terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] This configuration, known as the centralized or mainframe model, featured a powerful central computer that performed all the processing tasks, while terminals served as input/output devices for users to interact with the system.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] These systems were initially character based.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] A character-oriented terminal is a type of computer terminal that communicates with its host one character at a time, as opposed to a block-oriented terminal that communicates in blocks of data.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] When personal computers became ubiquitous in the 1980s, they offered the option of running software on the user's personal computer, providing an opportunity to replace the expensive and space consuming hardware terminals with something that had additional functions.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Immediately software became available, that could emulate the functions of the hardware terminals on a PC.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Examples of such software for DOS were Telix or Telemate, which was published in 1988 and could emulate a DEC VT102 terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Workstations, usually running versions of Unix, also became common in the 1980s.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Unix systems usually provided access to the command line with locally-attached or dial-up terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Unix workstations were designed to be used primarily through a graphical user interface (GUI); to provide access to the command line, the GUI included terminal emulator applications that behaved like locally-attached terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Through the success of Linux on servers, especially running on data centers and cloud servers, the necessity of accessing remote computers through character-based terminal emulators remains.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators, such as xterm, implement additional features not present in the emulated terminal.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Additionally, programs have been developed to emulate assorted system console "terminals" such as the Sun workstation console and the Linux console.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Finally, some emulators simply refer to a set of standards, such as the standards for ANSI escape codes.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Such programs are available on many platforms, including DOS, Unix-like systems including Linux and macOS, Windows, and embedded operating systems found in cellphones and industrial hardware.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] In the past, Unix and Unix-like systems used serial port devices such as RS-232 ports, and provided `/dev/*` device files for them.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] With terminal emulators these device files are themselves emulated by a pair of pseudoterminal devices.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] These in turn emulate a physical port/connection to the host computing endpoint – hardware provided by operating system APIs, or software such as rlogin, telnet or SSH, among others.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] In Linux systems, for example, these would be `/dev/ptyp0` (for the master side) and `/dev/ttyp0` (for the slave side) pseudoterminal devices respectively.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] There are also special virtual console files like `/dev/console`.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] In text mode, writing to the file displays text on the virtual console and reading from the file returns text the user writes to the virtual console.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] As with other text terminals, there are also special escape sequences, control characters and functions that a program can use, most easily via a library such as *ncurses*.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] For more complex operations, the programs can use console and terminal special *ioctl* system calls.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] One can compare devices using the patterns vcs ("virtual console screen") and vcsa ("virtual console screen with attributes") such as `/dev/vcs1` and `/dev/vcsa1`.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators also include escape sequences for configuring the behavior of the terminal to facilitate good interoperation between the terminal and programs running inside of it, for example to configure paste bracketing.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] The virtual consoles can be configured in the file `/etc/inittab` read by *init*—typically it starts the text mode login process *getty* for several virtual consoles.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] X Window System can be configured in `/etc/inittab` or by an X display manager.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] A number of Linux distributions use systemd instead of init, which also allows virtual console configuration.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement a local echo function, which may erroneously be named "half-duplex", or still slightly incorrectly "echoplex" (which is formally an error detection mechanism rather than an input display option).
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement local editing, also known as "line-at-a-time mode".
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] This is also mistakenly referred to as "half-duplex".
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] In this mode, the terminal emulator only sends complete lines of input to the host system.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] The user enters and edits a line, but it is held locally within the terminal emulator as it is being edited.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] It is not transmitted until the user signals its completion, usually with the ↵ Enter key on the keyboard or a "send" button of some sort in the user interface.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] At that point, the entire line is transmitted.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Line-at-a-time mode implies local echo, since otherwise the user will not be able to see the line as it is being edited and constructed.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] However, line-at-a-time mode is independent of echo mode and does not *require* local echo.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] When entering a password, for example, line-at-a-time entry with local editing is possible, but local echo is turned off (otherwise the password would be displayed).
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] The complexities of line-at-a-time mode are exemplified by the line-at-a-time mode option in the telnet protocol.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] To implement it correctly, the *Network Virtual Terminal* implementation provided by the terminal emulator program must be capable of recognizing and properly dealing with "interrupt" and "abort" events that arrive in the middle of locally editing a line.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] In asynchronous terminals data can flow in any direction at any time.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] In **synchronous terminals** a protocol controls who may send data when.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] IBM 3270-based terminals used with IBM mainframe computers are an example of **synchronous terminals**.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] They operate in an essentially "screen-at-a-time" mode (also known as block mode).
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Users can make numerous changes to a page, before submitting the updated screen to the remote machine as a single action.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators that simulate the 3270 protocol are available for most operating systems, for use both by those administering systems such as the z9, as well as those using the corresponding applications such as CICS.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Other examples of synchronous terminals include the IBM 5250, ICL 7561, Honeywell Bull VIP7800 and Hewlett-Packard 700/92.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles, also called virtual terminals, are emulated text terminals, using the keyboard and monitor of a personal computer or workstation.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] The word "text" is key since virtual consoles are not GUI terminals and they do not run inside a graphical interface.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles are found on most Unix-like systems.
[src:rich-terminal/terminal-emulator] They are primarily used to access and interact with servers, without using a graphical desktop environment.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Like modern GUIs, they can use the entire screen area and may accept mouse and other inputs.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] They may also use color and often structure the display using box-drawing characters such as ┌ and ╣.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The modern context of use is usually a terminal emulator.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] In the early years of computing, text terminals were usually keyboard/printer devices.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Currently, however, keyboard/display devices dominate.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Examples are TN3270, xterm for X Window System and win32 console (in a window mode) for Microsoft Windows.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] This usually supports programs that expect a real text mode display, but may run considerably slower.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Certain functions of an advanced text mode, such as an own font uploading, almost certainly become unavailable.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The communication capabilities usually become reduced to a serial line or its emulation, possibly with few ioctl()s as an out-of-band channel in such cases as Telnet and Secure Shell.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] This is the worst case, because software restrictions hinder the use of capabilities of a remote display device.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] From text application's point of view, the display type is determined by the API, e.g., curses, TPUT.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Under Linux and other Unix-like systems, a program easily accommodates to any of the three cases because the same interface (namely, standard streams) controls the display and keyboard.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Many TUI programming libraries are available to help developers build TUI applications.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] American National Standards Institute (ANSI) standard ANSI X3.64 defines a standard set of escape sequences that can be used to drive terminals to create TUIs (see ANSI escape code).
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Escape sequences may be supported for all three cases mentioned in the above section, allowing arbitrary cursor movements and color changes.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] However, not all terminals follow this standard, and many non-compatible but functionally equivalent sequences exist.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] On IBM PC compatibles, the Basic Input Output System (BIOS) and MS-DOS system calls provide a way to write text on the screen, and the ANSI.SYS driver could process standard ANSI escape sequences.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] However, programmers soon learned that writing data directly to the screen buffer was far faster and simpler to program, and less error-prone; see VGA-compatible text mode for details.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] This change in programming methods resulted in many DOS TUI programs.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The Windows console environment is notorious for its emulation of certain EGA/VGA text mode features, particularly random access to the text buffer, even if the application runs in a window.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] On the other hand, programs running under Windows (both native and DOS applications) have much less control of the display and keyboard than Linux and DOS programs can have, because of aforementioned Windows console layer.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Most often those programs used a blue background for the main screen, with white or yellow characters, although commonly they had also user color customization.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] They often used box-drawing characters in IBM's code page 437.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Later, the interface became deeply influenced by graphical user interfaces (GUI), adding pull-down menus, overlapping windows, dialog boxes and GUI widgets operated by mnemonics or keyboard shortcuts.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Soon mouse input was added – either at text resolution as a simple colored box or at graphical resolution thanks to the ability of the Enhanced Graphics Adapter (EGA) and Video Graphics Array (VGA) display adapters to redefine the text character shapes by software – providing additional functions.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Some notable programs of this kind were Microsoft Word, DOS Shell, WordPerfect, Norton Commander, Turbo Vision based Borland Turbo Pascal and Turbo C (the latter included the conio library), Lotus 1-2-3 and many others.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Some of these interfaces survived even during the Microsoft Windows 3.1x period in the early 1990s.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] For example, the Microsoft C 6.0 compiler, used to write true GUI programs under 16-bit Windows, still has its own TUI.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Since its start, Microsoft Windows includes a console to display DOS software.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Later versions added the Windows console as a native interface for command-line interface and TUI programs.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The console usually opens in window mode, but it can be switched to full, true text mode screen and vice versa by pressing the Alt and Enter keys together.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Full-screen mode is not available in Windows Vista and later, but may be used with some workarounds.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Windows Terminal is a multi-tabbed terminal emulator that Microsoft has developed for Windows 10 and later as a replacement for Windows Console.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The Windows Subsystem for Linux which was added to Windows by Microsoft in 2019, supports running Linux text-based apps on Windows, within Windows console, Windows Terminal, and other Windows-based terminals.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] In Unix-like operating systems, TUIs are often constructed using the terminal control library *curses*, or *ncurses* (a mostly compatible library), or the alternative *S-Lang* library.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The advent of the *curses* library with Berkeley Unix created a portable and stable API for which to write TUIs.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The ability to talk to various text terminal types using the same interfaces led to more widespread use of "visual" Unix programs, which occupied the entire terminal screen instead of using a simple line interface.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] This can be seen in text editors such as vi, mail clients such as pine or mutt, system management tools such as SMIT, SAM, FreeBSD's Sysinstall and web browsers such as lynx.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Some applications, such as w3m, and older versions of pine and vi use the less-able termcap library, performing many of the functions associated with curses within the application.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Custom TUI applications based on *widgets* can be easily developed using the dialog program (based on ncurses), or the Whiptail program (based on S-Lang).
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] In addition, the rise in popularity of Linux brought many former DOS users to a Unix-like platform, which has fostered a DOS influence in many TUIs.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The program minicom, for example, is modeled after the popular DOS program Telix.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Some other TUI programs, such as the Twin desktop, were ported over.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Most Unix-like operating systems (Linux, FreeBSD, etc.) support virtual consoles, typically accessed through a Ctrl-Alt-F key combination.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] For example, under Linux up to 64 consoles may be accessed (12 via function keys), each displaying in full-screen text mode.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The free software program GNU Screen provides for managing multiple sessions inside a single TUI, and so can be thought of as being like a window manager for text-mode and command-line interfaces.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The proprietary macOS text editor BBEdit includes a *shell worksheet* function that works as a full-screen shell window.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The free Emacs text editor can run a shell inside of one of its buffers to provide similar functionality.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] There are several shell implementations in Emacs, but only `ansi-term` is suitable for running TUI programs.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The other common shell modes, `shell` and `eshell` only emulate command lines and TUI programs will complain "Terminal is not fully functional" or display a garbled interface.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The free Vim and Neovim text editors have terminal windows (simulating xterm).
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] The feature is intended for running jobs, parallel builds, or tests, but can also be used (with window splits and tab pages) as a lightweight terminal multiplexer.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] VAX/VMS (later known as OpenVMS) had a similar facility to *curses* known as the Screen Management facility or SMG.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] This could be invoked from the command line or called from programs using the SMG$ library.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Another kind of TUI is the primary interface of the Oberon operating system, first released in 1988 and still maintained.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Unlike most other text-based user interfaces, Oberon does not use a text-mode console or terminal, but requires a large bit-mapped display, on which text is the primary target for mouse clicks.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Analogous to a link in hypertext, a command has the format `Module.Procedure *parameters* ~` and is activated with a mouse middle-click.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Text displayed anywhere on the screen can be edited, and if formatted with the required command syntax, can be middle-clicked and executed.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Any text file containing suitably-formatted commands can be used as a so-called **tool text**, thus serving as a user-configurable menu.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Even the output of a previous command can be edited and used as a new command.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] This approach is radically different from both conventional dialogue-oriented console menus or command-line interfaces but bears some similarities to the worksheet interface of the Macintosh Programmer's Workshop.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Since it does not use graphical widgets, only plain text, but offers comparable functionality to a GUI with a tiling window manager, it is referred to as a Text User Interface or TUI.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] For a short introduction, see the 2nd paragraph on page four of the first published *Report on the Oberon System*.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Oberon's UI influenced the design of the Acme text editor and email client for the Plan 9 from Bell Labs operating system.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Modern embedded systems are capable of displaying TUI on a monitor like personal computers.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] This functionality is usually implemented using specialized integrated circuits, modules, or using FPGA.
[src:rich-terminal/text-based-user-interface] Video circuits or modules are usually controlled using VT100-compatible command set over UART, FPGA designs usually allow direct video memory access.
